Thanks,<br />I have posted onto the mailing list as you advised.<br /><br />Proper sanitation of user input will solve all XSS problems, but it is a fragile solution; it relies on every website correctly sanitising every source of user input all the time.  Having a second line of defence (i.e. scripts not working in the body) seems sensible to me.<br /><br />It's analogous to the problem of buffer overruns, where the correct solution is for all C-style programs to correctly allocate memory for buffers. But because a single buffer overrun can have such a terrible security impact, more levels of defence are introduced such as address space layout randomisation.  We know that we cannot expect perfect security from all code paths.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=2020">RobLev</a> — Thu Jul 28, 2011 10:11 pm</p><hr />
